The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Traffic sergeants and pedestrians on Monday afternoon chased down a taxi driver, who was allegedly misbehaving with his two young woman passengers. Sambhu Roy, the 27-year-old driver, was arrested in Doctors Lane, at Taltala, on charges of eve-teasing. The women had boarded the taxi around 1.40 pm on CIT Road and asked Roy to take them to New Market. After some time, the driver allegedly started making indecent proposals to the girls and increased the speed of the vehicle when they asked him to stop. As the taxi hit SN Banerjee Road, the women started screaming. Three sergeants started chasing the cab. The driver stopped the taxi in Doctors Lane and tried to run away, but was caught by pedestrians.

 Mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya has directed municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay to take stern action against shop-owners using pavements and carriageways to display and store their goods. The mayor has also called for action against hawkers encroaching upon the carriageway.

 The Calcutta Municipal Corporation has decided to slap a notice on soft drink companies for putting up advertisements on delivery trucks without paying display tax.

 Trader Sheikh Panchu, 38, sustained serious injuries after being assaulted with a chopper by criminals in Rajabazar on Monday evening. He was admitted to NRS Hospital.

 The eyesight of drivers will be tested free at various points in the city till January 14, as part of Calcutta Polices traffic awareness week.

 Sri Ram Sau, 37, a resident of Shibpur, Howrah, was run over by an unidentified vehicle on Sunday evening near his home. He died at Howrah General Hospital. 

 ILS Multispeciality Clinic has been granted accreditation for offering post-doctoral fellowship in minimal access surgery by National Board of Examinations, under the Union ministry of health and family welfare.

